==Old English==
===Etymology===
Representing Indo-European ''*swe-, *se-''.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[sa]], Old Saxon [[so|sō]] (Dutch [[zo]]), Old High German [[so|sō]] (German [[so]]), Old Norse [[svá]] (Swedish [[så]]), Gothic [[𐍃𐍅𐌰]], Latin [[si]] (from an earlier form ''suad''), Oscan [[svai|svaí]], Umbrian [[sve]], Greek [[ὡς]] (earlier '''*ϝος''').

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /swa:/

===Pronoun===
'''swā'''
# that, of that
#:''Æt men fiftene peningas, and æt horse healf swa'': 15 pennies for a man, and half that for a horse.

===Adverb===
'''swā'''
# [[so]], [[thus]]
#:''Nis hit na swa'': it is not so.
# to the extent stated; to a great extent, [[so]], [[very]]
#:''Ðu meaht swa wide geseon'': you could see so far.
# doubled as a correlative: the...the...
#:''Swa norðor swa smælre'': the further north, the narrower the land.
# doubled as a comparative: as...as...
#:''Swa hwit swa snaw'': as white as snow.

===Conjunction===
'''swā'''
# [[so]], with the result that
# on condition that

